THE NIGHT was a blue-white glare from slave lights hanging in their carrier beams above the street. People in the costumes of many nations and many regions, a multicolored river of people, flowed past the }{
\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 A\rquote Chigua}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  toward the Plaza.
\par Martinho sped up, led his men into the stream. People made way, words of recognition followed.
\par \'93It\rquote s Joao Martinho and some of his Irmandades.\'94
\par \'93\'85 the Piratininga with Benito Alvarez.\'94
\par \'93Joao Martinho\'85\'94
\par At the Plaza, a white truck of the Hermosillo Bandeirantes played its searchlights on the fountain. There were other trucks and official vehicles across the way. The Hermosillo truck was a working rig recently returned from the interlands, by
 the look of it. The interleavings of its extensile wings were still streaked with dirt. The break-line of its forward pod could be distinguished clearly\emdash a distinct crack that ran completely around the vehicle. Two of its ground-lift pods didn
\rquote t quite match the white of the others, evidence of a field repair job.
\par Martinho followed the pointing fingers of the searchlights. He moved forward to a line of police and bandeirantes holding back the crowd, was passed through on recognition, his men following.
\par \'93Where\rquote s Ramon?\'94 Martinho asked.
\par Vierho pressed up close beside him, said, \'93Ramon went for the truck with Thome and Lon. I don\rquote t see a\rquote chigua.\'94
\par \'93But look you,\'94 Martinho said, pointing.
\par The crowd was being held back all around the Plaza at a distance of about fifty meters from the central fountain which rose in spooling, glistening arcs. 
In front of the crowd lay a tiled circle, its mosaic surface decorated with figures of the birds of Brazil. Inside this tiled ring, a ten-centimeter lip lifted to a circle of gre
en lawn about twenty meters in diameter with the fluted cup of the fountain in the center. Between tile and fountain the lawn showed yellow splotches of dead grass. Martinho\rquote s pointing finger picked out these patches one by one.
\par \'93Acid,\'94 Vierho whispered.
\par The searchlights centered abruptly on a shifting movement within the spray at the fountain\rquote s rim. A hissing passed through the crowd like a sudden wind.
\par \'93And there it is,\'94 Martinho said. \'93Now, will the so-suspicious official of the IEO believe?\'94
\par As he spoke, a scintillant spray arched from the creature at the fountain and out onto the lawn. \'93}{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Eeee-ahhhh}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 
,\'94 the crowd said.
\par Martinho grew conscious of a low moaning off to his left, turned to see a doctor being directed there along the inner rim of the crowd. The 
doctor turned into the crowd on the other side of the Hermosillo truck, lifting his bag over his head as he entered the press of people.
\par \'93Who was hurt?\'94 Martinho asked.
\par One of the police behind him said, \'93It is Alvarez. He tried to get that\'85 thing, but he took only a handshield and a sprayrifle. The shield was not proof against a\rquote chigua\rquote s quickness. It got Alvarez in the arm.\'94
\par Vierho tugged at Martinho\rquote s sleeve, pointed into the crowd behind the policeman. Rhin Kelly and Chen-Lhu were being passed through the onlookers there, space being made for them as people recognized the IEO insignia.
\par Rhin waved, called, \'93Senhor Martinho\emdash that thing is impossible! It\rquote s at least seventy-five centimeters long. It must weigh three or four kilos.\'94
\par \'93Do they not believe their own eyes?\'94 Vierho asked.
\par Chen-Lhu came up to the policeman who\rquote d described the injury to Alvarez, said, \'93Let us through, please.\'94
\par \'93Eh? Oh\'85 yes, sir.\'94 The line of guards parted.
\par Chen-Lhu stopped beside the bandeirante leader, glanced down at Rhin, back to Martinho. \'93I don\rquote t believe it, either. I\rquote d give a pretty to get my hands on that\'85 thing.\'94
\par \'93What is it you don\rquote t believe?\'94 Martinho asked.
\par \'93I think it\rquote s some kind of automaton. Not so, Rhin?\'94
\par \'93It has to be,\'94 she said.
\par \'93How much of a pretty would you give?\'94 Martinho asked.
\par \'93Ten thousand cruzados.\'94
\par \'93Please keep the lovely }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Doctor Kelly}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  back here out of range,\'94 Martinho said. He turned to Vierho. \'93
What\rquote s keeping Ramon and that truck? Find them. I want our magna-glass shield and a modified sprayrifle.\'94
\par \'93Jefe!\'94
\par \'93At once. Oh, yes\emdash and get a large specimen bottle.\'94
\par Vierho sighed, turned away to obey.
\par \'93What do you say that thing is?\'94 Chen-Lhu asked.
\par \'93I don\rquote t have to say.\'94
\par \'93Do you imply it\rquote s one of the }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 things}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  which none but bandeirantes appear to see in the interlands?\'94

\par \'93I don\rquote t deny what my own eyes see.\'94
\par \'93Why have }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 we}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  never seen specimens, I wonder?\'94 Chen-Lhu mused.
\par Martinho swallowed to suppress an angry outburst. This fool safe back here in the Green! He dared to question what the bandeirantes knew for fact!
\par \'93Isn\rquote t that an interesting question?\'94 Chen-Lhu asked.
\par \'93We\rquote ve been lucky to get out with just our lives,\'94 Martinho growled.
\par \'93Any entomologist will tell you that thing\rquote s a physical impossibility,\'94 Rhin said.
\par \'93The material won\rquote t support such structure through that sort of activity,\'94 Chen-Lhu said.
\par \'93I can see the entomologists must be correct,\'94 Martinho said.
\par Rhin stared up at him. The angry cynicism surprised her. He attacked and did not remain on the defensive. He acted like a man who believed that }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 impossibility}{
\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  out there at the fountain actually was a giant insect. But in the night club he\rquote d argued the other side.
\par \'93You\rquote ve seen such things in the jungle?\'94 Chen-Lhu asked.
\par \'93Did you not see the scar on Vierho\rquote s face?\'94
\par \'93What does a scar prove?\'94
\par \'93We have seen\'85 what we have seen.\'94
\par \'93But an insect cannot grow that large!\'94 Rhin protested. She turned her attention to the dark creature dancing along the fountain\rquote s rim behind the curtain of water.
\par \'93So I\rquote ve been told,\'94 Martinho said. He wondered then about the reports from the Serra Dos Parecis. Mantidae three meters tall\emdash ten feet. He knew the argument against such a thing. Rhin\emdash 
all the entomologists were correct. Insects couldn\rquote t produce living structure that large. Was it possible the things were automata? Who\rquote d build such things? Why?
\par \'93It has to be a mechanical simulation of some kind,\'94 Rhin said.
\par \'93The acid\rquote s real, though,\'94 Chen-Lhu said. \'93Look at the yellow spots on the lawn.\'94
\par Martinho reminded himself then that his own basic training forced him to agree with Rhin and Chen-Lhu. He\rquote d even denied to Vierho that giant mantidae could exist. 
He knew how rumors pyramided. There were so few people other than bandeirantes in the Red areas these days. 
The Resettlement Plan had been most efficient. And there was no denying that many bandeirantes were semi-ignorant, superstitious men attracted only by the romance and money.
\par Martinho shook his head. He\rquote d been there on the Goyaz track the day Vierho had suffered the acid burn. He\rquote d seen\'85 what he had seen. And now, this creature at the fountain.
\par The high-pitched roaring hiss of truck motors intruded on his awareness. The sound grew louder. The crowd parted giving a wide berth to the ground blast as Ramon backed the Irmandades truck into position beside the Hermosillo vehicle. 
The rear doors opened and Vierho jumped down as the motors were silenced.
\par \'93Jefe,\'94 he called. \'93Why do we not use the truck? Ramon could put it almost up to the\'85\'94
\par Martinho waved him to silence, spoke to Chen-Lhu: \'93The truck does not have enough maneuverability. You saw how fast that thing is.\'94
\par \'93You haven\rquote t said what you think it is,\'94 Chen-Lhu said.
\par \'93I\rquote ll say when I see it in a specimen bottle,\'94 Martinho said.
\par Vierho came up beside him, said, \'93But the truck would give us\'85\'94
\par \'93No! Dr. Chen-Lhu desires an undamaged specimen. Get us some foam bombs. We go in with our hands.\'94
\par Vierho sighed, shrugged, returned to the rear of the truck, spoke briefly to someone inside. A bandeirante in the truck began passing out equipment.
\par Martinho turned to the policeman helping hold back the crowd, said, \'93Can you get a message to the vehicles across the way?\'94
\par \'93Of course, honorable sir.\'94
\par \'93I want their lights turned off. I don\rquote t want to risk being blinded by lights in front of me. You understand?\'94
\par \'93They will be told at once.\'94 He turned, relayed the message to an officer down the line.
\par Martinho strode to the rear of his truck, took a spray-rifle, examined the charge cylinder, extracted it, took another from a door rack. He locked in the charge, and again checked the rifle.
\par \'93Keep the specimen bottle here until we\rquote ve immobilized that\'85 thing,\'94 he said. \'93I\rquote ll call for it.\'94
\par Vierho rolled out the shield, a two-centimeter thickness of acid-resistant, tempered magna-glass, mounted on a two-wheeled handtruck. A narrow slot at the right accepted the rifle.
\par A bandeirante in the truck handed out two protective suits\emdash silver-gray fiberglass sandwiches encased in slick acid-resistant synthetic fabric.
\par Martinho slipped into one, examined the seals.
\par Vierho donned the other.
\par \'93I could use Thome on the shield,\'94 Martinho said.
\par \'93Thome has not as much experience, Jefe.\'94
\par Martinho nodded, began examining the foamal bombs and auxiliary equipment. He hung extra charge cylinders in a rack on the shield.
\par It was all done quickly and silently, with the ease of long experience. The crowd behind the truck took on some of their silence\emdash a charged waiting. Only the faintest murmuring of conversation surrounded the truck.
\par \'93It is still there on the fountain, Jefe,\'94 Vierho said.
\par He took the control handle of the shield, moved it out onto the mosaic tiles. The right wheel stopped on the patterned blue-scale neck of a condor worked into the tiles. Martinho rested his sprayrifle in its slot, said, \'93This\rquote 
d be easier if we only had to kill it.\'94
\par \'93Those things are quick as O Diablo,\'94 Vierho said. \'93I do not like this, Jefe. If that thing should get around our shield\'85\'94 He fingered the sleeve of his protective suit. \'93This would be like a piece of gauze trying to stop the river.\'94

\par \'93So don\rquote t let it get around the shield.\'94
\par \'93I will do my best, Jefe.\'94
\par Martinho studied the creature waiting behind the water curtain at the rim of the fountain, said, \'93Bring a handlight. Perhaps we can dazzle it.\'94
\par Vierho set the shield stand, returned to the truck. He was back in a moment with the light hanging from his belt.
\par \'93Let\rquote s go,\'94 Martinho said.
\par Vierho released the handtruck stand, activated its motors. A faint humming issued from it. He turned the driver handle two notches. The shield crept forward, levered its way over the raised ring of the Plaza onto the lawn.
\par A stream of acid arched outward from the creature at the fountain, splashed onto the grass ten meters in front of them. Oily white smoke boiled from the lawn, was dispersed to their left by a light breeze. 
Martinho noted the direction of the breeze, signaled for the shield to be turned upwind. They circled right.
\par Another stream of acid arched toward them, fell short about the same distance.
\par \'93It is trying to tell us something, Jefe,\'94 Vierho joked.
\par Slowly they approached it, crossed one of the yellowed patches of grass.
\par Again the stream lifted from the fountain rim. Vierho leaned the shield backward. Acid splashed onto the glass, ran down the front. A biting smell filled their nostrils.
\par A murmurous \'93}{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Ahhhhhhhh}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 \'94 lifted from the crowd around the Plaza.
\par \'93They are fools to stand that close, you know,\'94 Vierho said. \'93If that thing should charge\'85\'94
\par \'93Someone would shoot it with a hard-pellet,\'94 Martinho said. \'93Fini a\rquote chigua.\'94
\par \'93Fini Dr. Chen-Lhu\rquote s specimen,\'94 Vierho said. \'93Fini ten thousand cruzados.\'94
\par \'93Yes,\'94 Martinho said. \'93We must not forget why we run this risk.\'94
\par \'93I hope you don\rquote t believe I\rquote d do this for love,\'94 Vierho said. He inched the shield forward another meter.
\par A foggy area began to form where the acid had hit.
\par \'93Etched the magna-glass!\'94 Vierho said, astonishment filling his voice.
\par \'93Smelled something like Oxalic,\'94 Martinho said. \'93Must be stronger, though. Take it slow now. I want a sure shot.\'94
\par \'93Why don\rquote t you try a foam bomb?\'94
\par \'93Vierho!\'94
\par \'93Ahhh, yes: the water.\'94
\par The creature began sliding to their right along the fountain. Vierho turned the shield to cover this new approach. The creature stopped, retraced its steps.
\par \'93Wait a bit,\'94 Martinho said. He found a clear place in the glass, studied the thing.
\par The creature shifted back and forth, plainly visible on the fountain rim. It resembled its tiny namesake the way a caricature might. Its sectioned body appeared to be supported on ribbed legs that bowed outward to terminate in strong, gripping hairs. 
The antennae were stubby and glistened wetly at the ends.
\par Abruptly, it lifted a tubular nose, squirted a hard stream directly at the shield.
\par Martinho ducked involuntarily. \'93We must get closer,\'94 he said. \'93It must not have time to recover after I stun it.\'94
\par \'93With what have you charged the rifle, Jefe?\'94
\par \'93Our special mix\emdash dilute sulphur and corrosive sublimate in air-coagulating butyl carrier. I want to tangle its legs.\'94
\par \'93I wish you had also brought something to plug its nose.\'94
\par \'93Come along, old gray head,\'94 Joao said.
\par Vierho urged the shield closer, bent to peer past the acid fogging.
\par The giant chigger danced sideways, turned, darted off to the right along the fountain rim. Abruptly, it whirled, arched a stream of acid at them. The liquid glistened under the searchlights like a high curve of jewels. 
Vierho barely had time to swerve the shield into the new attack.
\par \'93By the blood of ten thousand saints,\'94 Vierho muttered. \'93I do not like working in this close to such a thing, Jefe. We are not fighters of bulls.\'94
\par \'93This is no bull, my brother. It hasn\rquote t the horns.\'94
\par \'93I think I would prefer the horns.\'94
\par \'93We talk too much,\'94 Martinho said. \'93Closer, eh?\'94
\par Vierho urged the shield ahead until a bare two meters separated them from the creature on the fountain. \'93Shoot it,\'94 he hissed.
\par \'93We will get only one shot,\'94 Martinho said. \'93I must not damage the specimen. The Doctor wishes a whole specimen.\'94
\par And he thought: }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 So do I}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 .
\par He swung the rifle toward the creature, but the chigger leaped to the lawn, back to the fountain rim. A scream lifted from the crowd.
\par Martinho and Vierho crouched, watching as their prey danced back and forth.
\par \'93Why doesn\rquote t it stand still for just a second?\'94 Martinho asked.
\par \'93Jefe, if it comes under the shield, we are cooked. Why do you wait? Pick it off.\'94
\par \'93I must be certain of it,\'94 Martinho said.
\par He swung the sprayrifle back and forth with the motions of the darting, dancing insect. It dodged away from the line of sight each time, moving farther and farther to the right. Suddenly, it turned, scuttled on around the fountain\rquote 
s rim to the opposite side. Now the entire water curtain separated them from it, but the searchlights had followed the retreat and they could still see it there.
\par Martinho entertained the odd suspicion then that the thing was trying to maneuver them into some special position. He lifted his suit\rquote s face shield, wiped his forehead with his left hand. 
He was perspiring heavily. It was a hot night, but here by the fountain there was cool mist in the air\emdash and the bitter smell of the acid.
\par \'93I think we are in trouble,\'94 Vierho said. \'93If it keeps the fountain between us, how will we capture it?\'94
\par \'93Come along,\'94 Martinho said. \'93If it stays across the fountain from us, I\rquote ll order out another team. It cannot dodge two teams.\'94
\par Vierho began maneuvering the shield sideways around the fountain. \'93I still think we should\rquote ve used the truck,\'94 he said.
\par \'93Too big and clumsy,\'94 Martinho said. \'93Besides, I think the truck might frighten it into attempting a break through the crowd. This way, it may feel it has a chance against us.\'94
\par \'93Jefe, I feel that same thing.\'94
\par The giant chigger took this moment to dart toward them, stop and crawl backwards. It kept its nose aimed at the shield and presented a steady target, but too much of the water curtain fell between it and Martinho for a safe shot.
\par \'93The wind is at our backs, Jefe,\'94 Vierho said.
\par \'93I know. Let\rquote s hope that thing hasn\rquote t the wit to shoot over our heads. The wind\rquote d drop acid onto our backs.\'94
\par The chigger backed into an area where the fountain\rquote s upper structure shadowed it from the searchlights. It shifted back and forth in the shadow area, a dark wet movement.
\par \'93Jefe, that thing is not going to stay there for long. I can feel it.\'94
\par \'93Hold the shield here a moment,\'94 Martinho said. \'93I think you\rquote re right. We ought to clear the Plaza. If it took it into its mind to rush the crowd, people would be hurt.\'94
\par \'93You say a true thing, Jefe.\'94
\par \'93Vierho, use the handlight. Try to dazzle its eyes. I\rquote ll break away from the shield to our right and try a long shot.\'94
\par \'93Jefe!\'94
\par \'93You have a better idea?\'94
\par \'93At least let us pull the shield farther out there into the lawn. You would not be so close if\'85\'94
\par Still in the shadows, the chigger hopped sideways off the fountain rim onto the lawn. Vierho jerked up the handlight, bathed the creature in a blue-white glare.
\par \'93O, Dios, Jefe! Shoot it!\'94
\par Martinho swung the sprayrifle around to bear on the new position, but the shield slot prevented a full swing. He cursed, grabbed for the control handle, but before he could swing the shield, 
a section of lawn the size of a street manhole lifted like a trapdoor behind the chigger and in the full glare of the handlight. A black shape with what appeared to be a triple-horned head emerged partly from the hole, sounded a rasping call.
\par The chigger darted past the shape and into the hole.
\par The crowd was screaming now, a noise compounded of rage, fear and feral excitement that filled the air of the plaza. Through it all, Martinho could hear Vierho praying in a low voice\emdash almost a chant: \'93Holy Mary, Mother of God\'85\'94
\par Martinho tried to push the shield around toward the creature in the hole, was stalled by Vierho trying to pull the structure backward. The shield twisted around on its wheels, exposing them to the black shape there as the thing lifted another ha
lf meter onto the lawn. Martinho had a full, clear look at it there bathed in the beam of the handlight. The thing looked like a gigantic stag beetle\emdash taller than a man and with triple horns.
\par Desperately, Martinho wrestled the sprayrifle from its shield slot, swung it toward the horned monster.
\par \'93Jefe, Jefe, Jefe!\'94 Vierho pleaded.
\par Martinho brought his weapon to bear, squeezed off a two-second charge, counting to himself: \'93One butterfly, two butterfly.\'94
\par The poison-butyl mixture slammed into the creature, enveloped it.
\par The creature, its shape distorted by the spray-mix, hesitated, then lifted farther out of the hole with a rasping, grunting sound heard clearly above the crowd screams.
\par The crowd fell abruptly silent as the thing towered there, a shell-backed monster\emdash green, black, glistening\emdash at least a meter taller than a man.
\par Martinho could hear a sucking, rasping sound from it, an odd wet noise like the sound of the fountain with which it competed.
\par Carefully, he again aimed the sprayrifle at the horned head\emdash point blank range\emdash and emptied the charge cylinder: ten seconds. 
The creature appeared to dissolve backward into its hole with eerie extensions and protrusions fighting the sticky butyl.
\par \'93Jefe, let us go away from here,\'94 Vierho pleaded. \'93}{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Please, Jefe}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 .\'94 He swung 
the shield around until it again stood between them and the giant insect. \'93Please,\'94 Vierho said. He began forcing Martinho back with the shield.
\par Martinho grabbed another charge cylinder, slammed it into his rifle, took a foamal bomb in his left hand. He felt emptied of every emotion except the need to attack that monster and kill it. 
But before he could draw his arm back to throw the bomb, he felt the shield buck. He looked up to a solid stream of liquid driving down on the shield from the black creature in the hole.
\par He needed no urging as Vierho screamed, \'93Run!\'94
\par They fled backward, dragging the shield.
\par The attack stopped as they drew out of range. Martinho stopped, looked back. He felt Vierho trembling beside him. The dark thing in the hole sank slowly backward. It was the most menacing retreat Martinho had ever seen. 
The movement radiated a willingness to return to the attack. It sank from sight. The section of lawn closed behind it.
\par As though that were the signal, the crowd sounds picked up all around the Plaza, but Martinho could hear the fear in the voices even when he couldn\rquote t make out the words.
\par He threw back his face shield, listening to the words like sharp cries, the snatches of sentences\emdash \'93Like a monster beetle!\'94 \'93Have you heard the report from the waterfront?\'94 \'93The whole region could be infested!\'94 \'93\'85
at the Monte Ochoa Convent\'85 orphanage\'85\'94
\par Through it all came the same question repeated from all sides of the Plaza: \'93What was it?\'94 \'93What was it?\'94 \'93What was it?\'94
\par Martinho felt someone at his right, jerked around to see Chen-Lhu standing there, eyes intent on the place where the beetle shape had disappeared. There was no sign of Rhin Kelly.
\par \'93Yes, Johnny,\'94 Chen-Lhu said. \'93What was it?\'94
