\par Martinho looked toward the place in the lawn where the giant figure of a beetle had disappeared. He found this dalliance with talk far more alluring than the walk across the lawn to that place. The night air carried a sense of lowering menace and\'85
 hysteria. And the oddest thing of all was the reluctance to take action that could be seen all around him. It was like the lull after a terrible battle in a war.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Well, it is a kind of war}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 , he told himself.
\par Eight years they\rquote d been fighting this war here in Brazil. The Chinese had taken twenty-two years, but they\rquote d said it could be done here in ten. The thought that it might take twenty-two years here\emdash fourteen more years\emdash 
momentarily threatened to overwhelm Martinho. He felt a monstrous fatigue.
\par \'93You must admit odd things are happening,\'94 Chen-Lhu said.
\par \'93That we admit,\'94 Alvarez said.
\par \'93Why does no one suspect the Carsonites?\'94 Vierho asked.
\par \'93A good question, Padre,\'94 Alvarez said. \'93They have big support, the Carsonites\emdash all the holdout nations: the U.S. of A., Canada, the United Kingdom, Common Europe.\'94
\par \'93All the places where they\rquote ve never had any real trouble with the insects,\'94 Vierho said.
\par Oddly, it was Chen-Lhu who protested. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93The holdout nations don\rquote t really care\emdash except that they\rquote re happy to see us occupied with this fight.\'94
