\par She stopped in front of him, spoke in a husky, urgent voice: \'93Senhor Martinho, I\rquote ve come to save your life.\'94
\par He shook his head, not quite believing he\rquote d heard her correctly. \'93What\'85\'94
\par \'93All hell is about to break loose,\'94 she said.
\par Martinho grew aware of distant shouting.
\par \'93A mob,\'94 she said. \'93Armed.\'94
\par \'93What the devil\rquote s going on?\'94 he demanded.
\par \'93There\rquote ve been some deaths tonight,\'94 she said. \'93Women and children among them. A section of the hill collapsed behind Monte Ochoa. There\rquote re burrows all through that hill.\'94
\par Vierho said, \'93The orphanage\'85\'94
\par \'93Yes,\'94 she said. \'93The orphanage and convent on Monte Ochoa were buried. Bandeirantes are blamed. You know what is being said about\'85\'94
\par \'93I\rquote ll talk to these people,\'94 Martinho said. He felt outrage at the thought of being threatened by those he served. \'93This is nonsense! We\rquote ve done nothing to\'85\'94
\par \'93Jefe,\'94 Vierho said, \'93you do not reason with a mob.\'94
\par \'93Two men of the Lifcado band already have been lynched,\'94 Rhin said. \'93You have a chance if you run now. Your trucks are here, enough for all of you.\'94
\par Vierho took his arm. \'93Jefe, we must do as she says.\'94
