\par The rhythmic pulsing of a yellow sac at one side pumped a dark viscous fluid into the brain. Wingless insects crawled over its surface membranes\emdash inspecting, repairing, giving special foods where needed.
\par Specialist hives of winged insects clustered in fissures of the cave, some producing acids, some breaking down the acids for their oxygen, some digesting, some providing the muscles for pumping.
\par A bitter-clean acid smell permeated the cave.
\par Insects flew in and out of the dawnlight. Some paused to dance and sway and hum for the brain\rquote 
s sensors; some used modulated stridulations to report; some appeared in special groups aligned a special way; some formed complex patterns with changes in coloration; some waved antennae in intricate ways.
