THE DANCING PATTERN of insects on the cave ceiling appeared as a lovely thing to the Brain. It admired the interplay of color and motion while it read the patterned message:
\par \'93Report from listeners in the savannah; acknowledge.\'94
\par The Brain signaled for the dance to proceed.
\par \'93Three humans prepare to flee in the small vehicle,\'94 danced the insects. \'93The vehicle will not fly. They will try to escape by floating away on the river. What do we do?\'94
\par The Brain paused to assess data. The trapped humans had been under observation twelve days. They\rquote d provided much information about their reactions under stress. The information expanded data obtained from captives under more direct control. 
Ways to immobilize and kill humans became more obvious daily. But the problem wasn\rquote t how to kill them. It was how to communicate with them in the absence of fear or stress on either side.
\par Some of the humans\emdash like the old one with the grand manner\emdash made offers and suggestions and appeared to display reason\'85 but could they be trusted? That was the key question.
\par The Brain felt a desperate need for observational data on humans under conditions it could control without that control being noticed. Discovery of the listening posts in the Green had aroused a frenzy of human activity. 
They used new sonotoxics, deepened their barriers, renewed their attacks on the Red.
\par Another worry compounded all this\emdash the unknown fate of four units which had penetrated the barriers before the Bahia catastrophe. Only one had returned; its report: \'93
We became twelve. Six gave up unit-identity to envelop the area where we captured the two human leaders. Their fate is unknown. One unit was destroyed. Four dispersed to produce more of us.\'94
\par Discovery of those four units at this time would be catastrophe, the Brain realized.
\par When would the simulacra emerge? That depended on local conditions\emdash temperature, available foods, chemicals, moisture. The lone unit that had returned had no knowledge of where the four had gone.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 We must find them!}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  the Brain thought.
\par The problems of individually-directed action dismayed the Brain then. The simulacra were a mistake. Many identical units would only attract disastrous attention.
\par That the simulacra meant no great harm and were conditioned only to limited violence had no meaning under present conditions. That they wanted only to be allowed to speak and to reason with human leaders\emdash this plan carried only pathos and irony now.

\par The reported words of the human called Chen-Lhu came back to plague the Brain: \'93}{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Debacle\'85 barren earth}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 .
\'94 This Chen-Lhu offered a way to solve their mutual problem, but what were his true intentions? Could he be trusted?
\par The Brain suspended decision, directed a question at its minions: \'93Which humans will try to escape?\'94
\par Attention must be paid to such details, the Brain knew. Hive orientation tended to ignore individuals. The error with the simulacra had originated in this tendency.
\par On the surface, the Brain knew its problem appeared deceptively simple. But just under the surface lay the hellish complications of emotional triggers. }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Emotions! Emotions!}{
\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  Reason had so many barriers to hurdle.
\par The messengers had consulted their listening-post data. Now they danced out the name sounds: \'93The latent queen, Rhin Kelly, and the ones called Chen-Lhu and Joao Martinho.\'94
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Martinho}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 , the Brain thought. That was the human from the other half of the airtruck. 
In this fact lay an indication of the humans\rquote  complicated quasi-hive kinship. There could be value in that relationship. And Chen-Lhu would be in the vehicle, as well.
\par The insects on the ceiling, having been bred with a repeat factor to insure communication, repeated their previous question:
\par \'93What counter action is required?\'94
\par \'93Message to all units,\'94 the Brain said. \'93The three in the vehicle will be allowed to escape to the river. Offer just enough resistance to make it appear we oppose the escape. They are to be followed by action grou
ps capable of disposing of them whenever necessary. As soon as the three have reached the river, overwhelm the ones who remain.\'94
\par Messenger units began assembling overhead, dancing the pattern to imprint it. They took off in compact groups, darting out of the cave-mouth into the sunlight.
\par The Brain admired the color and motion for a few minutes, then lowered its sensors, set itself to the problem of overcoming protein incompatibility.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 We must produce immediate and consequential benefits that the humans cannot fail to recognize}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 
, the Brain thought. }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 
If we can demonstrate dramatic usefulness, they may yet be brought to understand that inter-dependence is circular, inextricably entangled and a matter of life and death}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 .
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 They need us and we need them\'85 but the burden of proof has fallen on us. And if we fail to prove it, this will be truly barren earth.}{
\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 
\par \~
\par \'93It will be dark soon, Jefe,\'94 Vierho said. \'93You will go then.\'94 Vierho swung the pod\rquote s canopy forward, leaned into it.
\par Joao stood one step behind him, still feeling weak and plagued by occasional flash-cramps in his left leg above the energy pack. 
The direct feed and specialized hormones could only approximate the needs of a specific body, and Joao could feel himself half poised against strange tensions because of this treatment.
\par \'93I have put the food and other emergency supplies here under the seat,\'94 Vierho said. \'93There\rquote s more food in the gig-box there in the back. You have two sprayrifles with twenty spare charges, one hard-pellet carbine. I\rquote 
m sorry we have so little ammo for it. There\rquote re a dozen foamal bombs under the other seat, and I\rquote ve tied a hand-spray rig into the corner back there. It\rquote s fully charged.\'94
\par Vierho straightened, glanced back at the tents. His voice fell to a conspiratorial whisper. \'93Jefe, I do not trust the Doctor Chen-Lhu. I heard him when he thought he was dying. This new face is not like him.\'94
\par \'93It\rquote s a chance we have to take,\'94 Joao said. \'93I still think you or one of the others who weren\rquote t as sick should go in place of me.\'94
\par \'93No more talk of that, Jefe, please.\'94
\par Again Vierho\rquote s voice fell to the conspiratorial whisper: \'93Jefe, step close to me as though we are saying goodbye.\'94
\par Joao hesitated, then obeyed. He felt something metallic and heavy pushed into the belt pocket of his uniform. The pocket sagged with it. Joao pulled his jungle jacket around to cover the sag, whispered, \'93What\rquote s that?\'94
\par \'93It belonged to my great grandfather,\'94 Vierho said. \'93It is a pistol called the .475 Magnum. It has five bullets and here are two dozen more.\'94 Another packet was slipped into the side pocket of Joao\rquote s jacket. \'93It\rquote 
s not much good except against men,\'94 Vierho said.
\par Joao swallowed, felt tears dampen his eyes. All the Irmandades knew the Padre carried that old blunderbuss and wouldn\rquote t part with it. The fact that he parted with it now meant he expected to die here\emdash likely true.
\par \'93God go with you, Jefe,\'94 Vierho said.
\par Joao turned, looked to the river about five hundred meters away across the savannah. He could just glimpse the beach of the opposite shore, the wild growth there illuminated by the afternoon sun. 
The jungle lifted there in steady waves of color, its bold lines standing out in the flat light. The growth was a deep blue-green at the bottom, a sun-bleached sage at the top, and with flecks of yellow, red and ochre between. 
Above the green towered a candello tree with bat-falcon nests cluttering the forks of its branches. A twisted screen of lianas partly obscured a wall of mata-polo trees to the left.
\par \'93Fifteen minutes of fuel in the pod and that\rquote s all?\'94 Joao asked.
\par \'93Maybe a minute more, Jefe.\'94
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 We\rquote ll never make it with nothing but that river\rquote s current to move us}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 , Joao thought.
\par \'93Jefe, sometimes there\rquote s a wind on the river,\'94 Vierho said.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Christ, he doesn\rquote t expect us to sail that thing, does he?}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  
Joao wondered. He looked at Vierho, saw the deep weariness in the man\rquote s face, the scarecrow emaciation.
\par \'93That wind could cause trouble, Jefe,\'94 Vierho said. \'93I have used one of the pod\rquote s grapnel anchors to make a thing that will float just under the surface and provide some drag. It is called a sea anchor. It\rquote 
ll keep the nose of the pod into the wind.\'94
\par \'93That\rquote s a clever idea, Padre,\'94 Joao said.
\par And he wondered: }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Why do we play out this farce? We\rquote re going to die here, all of us\'85 either here or somewhere down that river}{
\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 . There were seven or eight hundred kilometers of that river\emdash rapids, chasms, waterfalls\emdash and the rainy season was almost on them. 
The river would become a torrential hell. And if it didn\rquote t get them, there were always the new insects, the creatures of acid and sophisticated poisons.
\par \'93You better inspect it one more time yourself, Jefe,\'94 Vierho said. He gestured at the pod.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Yes, anything to keep busy, to keep from thinking}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 , Joao thought. He\rquote 
d already been over it once, but another look wouldn\rquote t hurt anything. After all, their lives would depend on it\'85 for awhile.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 Our lives!}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 
\par Joao allowed himself to wonder then if escape were possible, if there were any hope at all. This was, after all, the pod of a jungle airtruck. It could be sealed against most insects. It was designed to take abuse.
\par }{\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 I mustn\rquote t allow myself to hope}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 , he thought.
\par But he set himself to another inspection of the pod\'85 just in case.
\par The white bandeirante paint of its exterior had been washed away in patches, streaked and etched by acid. The float skids, normally long and faired extrusions of the pod\rquote s bottom curve, had been cranked out manually and locked in position. 
They formed a flat step up to the stub wings and into the cabin. The entire pod was just short of five and a half meters long with two meters at the rear taken up by the rocket motors. 
The motor complex which had nested into the discarded rear truck section was cut off flat on both sides. The pod itself was roughly oval in cross section. This left two flat half-moon surfaces which opened into the rear bulkhead of the pod\rquote 
s cabin. The left-side half-moon was a maze of male and female connectors which once had linked the pod to the truck section. The right side was sealed by a hatch which now opened from the cabin and down to one of the float skids.
\par Joao inspected the hatch, made certain the connectors had all been sealed off, looked at the right-side float skid. A jagged rent in the side of the float had been patched with butyl and fabric.
\par He could smell rocket fuel, and he knelt to peer up at the belly tank section. Vierho had siphoned out the fuel, applied a chemical hotpatch on the outside and spray-tank sealant inside, then replaced the fuel.
\par \'93It should hold all right if you don\rquote t hit anything,\'94 Vierho said.
\par Joao nodded, worked his way around, climbed up on the left stub wing and looked down into the cabin. Dual control seats forward and the padded gig-box in the rear. 
Spray stains were all over the interior. The interior formed a space about two meters square and two and a half meters deep. Windows in front looked down over the rounded nose. Side windows stopped at the wings forward, dipped deeper in the rear. 
A single transparent panel of polarizing plastic ran over the top to the rear bulkhead.
\par Joao let himself down into the command seat on the left, checked the manual controls. They felt loose and sluggish. New fuel-monitoring and firing controls had been installed with crude, hand-lettered labels. Vierho spoke at his shoulder.
\par \'93I had to use whatever was available, Jefe. There was not much. I\rquote m glad these IEO people were such fools.\'94
\par \'93Hmmm?\'94 Joao spoke absently as he continued his examination.
\par \'93When they left their truck, they took tents. I would\rquote ve taken more weapons. But the tents gave me the new guy cables and fabric for patches.\'94
\par Joao finished tracing the fuel controls. \'93No automatic demand valves on the fuel lines,\'94 he said.
\par \'93They couldn\rquote t be repaired, Jefe\emdash but you don\rquote t have much fuel anyway.\'94
