\par The thought turned every shadow outside into a source of peril, and Chen-Lhu wondered at himself that he could have allowed his mind to play such a fear-inspiring trick.
\par Still, he strained his senses against the night.
\par There was a waiting-silence outside, a feeling of presence in the jungle.
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 This is nonsense!}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  Chen-Lhu told himself.
\par He cleared his throat.
\par Joao turned against the seat, felt Rhin\rquote s head cradled against him. How quietly she breathed.
\par \'93Travis,\'94 he whispered.
\par \'93Yes?\'94
\par \'93Time\rquote s it?\'94
\par \'93Go back to sleep, Johnny. You\rquote ve a couple more hours.\'94
\par Joao closed his eyes, lay back into his seat, but deep sleep evaded him. Something about the cabin\'85 something. There was something here demanding his recognition. His awareness came farther and farther out of sleep.
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 Mildew}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 .
\par It was stronger in the cabin than it had been\emdash and there was the acrid tang of rust.
\par The smells filled Joao with melancholy. He could feel the pod deteriorating around him, and the pod was a symbol of civilization. These imperative odors represented all human decay and mortality.
\par He stroked Rhin\rquote s hair, thought: }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 Why shouldn\rquote t we grab a little happiness here, now? Tomorrow we could be dead\'85 or worse}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 .
\par Slowly, he sank back into sleep.
