\par A flock of parakeets announced the dawn. They chattered and gossiped in the jungle beside the river. Smaller birds joined the chorus\emdash flutterings, chirps, twitters.
\par Joao heard the birds as though from an enormous distance pulling him upward to wakefulness. He awoke, sweating, feeling oddly weak.
\par Rhin had moved away from him in the night. She slept curled against her side of the cabin.
\par Joao stared out at blue-white light. Smoky mist hid the river upstream and downstream. There was a feeling of moist, unhealthy warmth in the closed cabin\rquote s air. His mouth tasted dry and bitter.
\par He sat up straight, leaned forward to look through the overhead curve of windshield. His back ached from sleeping in a cramped position.
\par \'93Don\rquote t look up for searchers, Johnny,\'94 Chen-Lhu said.
\par Joao coughed, said, \'93I was just looking at the weather. We\rquote re going to get rain soon.\'94
\par \'93Perhaps.\'94
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 So gray, that sky}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 , Joao thought. It was an empty slate prepared as a setting for one vulture that sailed into view across the treetops, wings motionless. The vulture tipped majestically, beat its wings once
\'85 twice\'85 and flew upstream.
\par Joao lowered his gaze, noted that the pod had become part of a drifting island of logs and brush during the night. He could see parasite moss on the logs. It was an old island\emdash at least one season old\'85 no, }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 older}{
\cf1\insrsid15279183 . The moss was thick.
\par As he watched, an eddy came between the pod and the logs. They parted company.
\par \'93Where are we?\'94 Rhin asked.
\par Joao turned to see her sitting up, awake. She avoided his eyes.
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 What the hell?}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  he thought. }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 Is she ashamed?}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 
\par \'93We are where we\rquote ve always been, my dear Rhin,\'94 Chen-Lhu said. \'93We\rquote re on the river. Are you hungry?\'94
\par She considered the question, found that she was ravenous.
\par \'93Yes, I\rquote m hungry.\'94
\par They ate in quick silence with Joao growing more and more convinced that Rhin was avoiding him. She was first out the hatch to the float and stayed a long time. When she returned, she lay back in the seat, pretending sleep.
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 To hell with her}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 , Joao thought. He went out the hatch, slammed it after him.
\par Chen-Lhu leaned forward, whispered close to Rhin\rquote s ear, \'93You were very good last night, my dear.\'94
\par She spoke without opening her eyes: \'93To hell with you.\'94
\par \'93But I don\rquote t believe in hell.\'94
\par \'93And I do?\'94 She opened her eyes, stared at him.
\par \'93Of course.\'94
\par \'93Each in his own way,\'94 she said, and she closed her eyes.
\par For some reason he couldn\rquote t explain, her words and action angered him, and he tried to goad her with what he knew of her beliefs: \'93You are a terrible aboriginal calamity!\'94
\par Again, she spoke without opening her eyes: \'93That\rquote s Cardinal Newman. Stuff Cardinal Newman.\'94
\par \'93You don\rquote t believe in original sin?\'94 he jeered.
\par \'93I only believe in certain kinds of hell,\'94 she said, and again she was looking at him, the green eyes steady.
\par \'93To each his own, eh?\'94
\par \'93You said it; I didn\rquote t.\'94
\par \'93But you did say it.\'94
\par \'93Is that right?\'94
\par \'93Yes! You said it!\'94
\par \'93You\rquote re shouting,\'94 she said.
\par He took a moment to calm himself, then, in a whisper: \'93And Johnny, was he good?\'94
\par \'93Better than you could ever be.\'94
\par Joao opened the hatch and entered the cabin before Chen-Lhu could answer, found Rhin staring up at him.
\par \'93Howdy, Jefe,\'94 she said. And she smiled, a warm, intimate, sharing smile.
\par Joao answered the smile, slipped into his seat. \'93We\rquote re going to hit rapids today,\'94 he said. \'93I can feel it. What were you shouting about, Travis?\'94
\par \'93It was nothing,\'94 Chen-Lhu said, but his voice still grated with anger.
\par \'93It was an ideological issue,\'94 Rhin said. \'93Travis remains a militant atheist to the end. Me, I believe in heaven.\'94 She stroked Joao\rquote s cheek.
\par \'93Why do you think we are near rapids?\'94 Chen-Lhu asked. And he thought: }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 I must divert this conversation! This is a dangerous game you play with me, Rhin}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 .
\par \'93Current\rquote s faster, for one thing,\'94 Joao said. He stared out the front windows. A new, surging character definitely had come over the river. Hills had drawn closer to the channel. More eddies trailed their lines from the shores.
