THERE WAS a dream of being carried, a dream of tears and shouting, a dream of violent protests and defiance and rejection.
\par Joao woke to yellow-orange light and the figure that could not be his father bending over him, thrusting a hand out, saying, \'93Then examine my hand if you don\rquote t believe!\'94
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 It cannot be my father}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 , Joao thought. }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 I am dead\'85 he is dead. They\rquote ve copied him\'85 mimicry, nothing more}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 .
\par Numbing shock invaded Joao\rquote s awareness then.
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 How am I here?}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  he wondered. His mind searched back through memories and he saw himself killing Rhin with Vierho\rquote s old blunderbuss, then turning the weapon on himself.
\par Something moved behind the figure that couldn\rquote t be his father. Joao\rquote s attention jerked that way, saw a giant face at least two meters tall. It was a baleful face in the strange light, eyes brilliant and glaring\'85
 enormous eyes with pupils within pupils. The face turned and Joao saw that it could be no more than two centimeters thick. Again, the face turned. The strange eyes focused toward Joao\rquote s feet.
\par Joao forced himself to look down, lifting his head, then falling back with a violent trembling. Where his feet should have been he\rquote d s
een a foaming green cocoon. Joao lifted his left hand, remembering that it had been broken, but the arm came up without pain and he saw that his skin shared the green tones of that repellent cocoon.
\par \'93Examine my hand!\'94 ordered the old-man figure beside him. \'93I command it!\'94
\par \'93He is not quite awake.\'94
\par It was a booming voice, resonant, shaking the air all around them, and it seemed to Joao that the voice came from somewhere beneath that giant face.
\par }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 What nightmare is this?}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  Joao asked himself. }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 Am I in hell?}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 
\par With an abrupt, violent motion, Joao reached up, clutched the proffered hand.
\par It felt warm\'85 human.
\par Tears flooded Joao\rquote s eyes. He shook his head to clear them, remembered\'85 somewhere\'85 doing that same thing. But there were more pressing matters than memories. The hand felt real\'85 his tears felt real.
\par \'93How can this be?\'94 he whispered.
\par \'93Joao, my son,\'94 said his father\rquote s voice.
\par Joao peered up at the familiar face. It }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 was}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  his father and no mistaking, down to the very last feature. \'93But\'85 your heart,\'94 Joao said.
\par \'93My pump,\'94 the old man said. \'93Look.\'94 He pulled his hand away, turned to display where the back of his suit had been cut away. Its edges appeared to be held by some gummy substance. An oily yellow surface pulsed between those fabric edges.

\par Joao saw the hair-fine scale lines, the multiple shapes. He recoiled.
\par So it was a copy, another of their tricks.
\par The old man turned back to face him, and Joao couldn\rquote t avoid the youthful look of glee in the eyes. They weren\rquote t faceted, those eyes.
\par \'93The old pump failed and they gave me a new one,\'94 his father said. \'93It shares my blood and lives off me. It\rquote ll give me a few more useful years. What do you think our medical men will say about that?\'94
\par \'93It\rquote s really you,\'94 Joao gasped.
\par \'93All except the pump,\'94 the old man said. \'93But you, you stupid fool! What a mess you made of yourself and that poor woman.\'94
\par \'93Rhin,\'94 Joao whispered.
\par \'93Blew out your hearts and parts of your lungs,\'94 his father said. \'93And you fell right into the middle of all that corrosive poison you\rquote d sprayed all over the landscape. They
 not only had to give the two of you new hearts, but whole new blood systems!\'94
\par Joao lifted his hands, stared at the green skin. He felt dazzled by it and unable to escape a dream quality in his surroundings.
\par \'93They know medical tricks we haven\rquote t even imagined,\'94 his father said. \'93I haven\rquote t been this excited since I was a boy. I can hardly wait to get back and\'85 Joao! What is it?\'94
\par Joao thrust himself up, glared at the old man. \'93We\rquote re not human anymore! We\rquote re not human if\'85 We\rquote re not human!\'94
\par \'93Oh, be still,\'94 his father ordered.
\par \'93If this is\'85 They\rquote re in control!\'94 Joao protested. He forced his gaze onto the giant face behind his father. \'93They\rquote ll }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 rule}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  us!\'94
\par He sank back, gasping.
\par \'93We\rquote ll be their slaves,\'94 Joao whispered.
\par \'93Such foolishness,\'94 the drum-voice rumbled.
\par \'93He always was melodramatic,\'94 the elder Martinho said. \'93Look at the mess he made of things out there on the river. Of course, }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 you}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  had a hand in that. If you\rquote d only listened to me, trusted me.
\'94
\par \'93Now we have a hostage,\'94 the Brain rumbled. \'93Now we can afford to trust you.\'94
\par \'93You\rquote ve had a hostage ever since you put this pump in me,\'94 the old man said.
\par \'93I didn\rquote t understand the price you put on the individual unit,\'94 the Brain said. \'93After all, }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 we\rquote ll}{\cf1\insrsid15279183  spend almost any unit to save the hive.\'94
\par \'93Not a queen,\'94 the old man said. \'93You won\rquote t spend a queen. And how about yourself? Would you spend yourself?\'94
\par \'93Unthinkable,\'94 the Brain muttered.
\par Slowly, Joao turned his head, looked beneath the giant face to where the voice originated. He saw a white mass about four meters 
across, a pulsing yellow sac protruding from it. Wingless insects crawled over it, into fissures along its surface and along the stone floor of the cave underneath. The face reared up from that mass supported by dozens of round stalks. Their scaled surfac
es betrayed their nature.
\par The reality of the situation began to penetrate Joao\rquote s shock.
\par \'93Rhin?\'94 he whispered.
\par \'93Your mate is safe,\'94 the Brain rumbled. \'93Changed like yourself, but safe.\'94
\par Joao continued to stare at the white mass on the cave floor. He saw that the voice issued from the pulsing yellow sac.
\par \'93Your attention is drawn to our way of answering your threat to us,\'94 the Brain said. \'93This is our brain. It is vulnerable, yet strong\'85 just as your brain.\'94
\par Joao fought down a shiver of revulsion.
\par \'93Tell me,\'94 the Brain said, \'93how you define slave.\'94
\par \'93I\rquote m a slave now,\'94 Joao whispered. \'93I\rquote m in bondage to you. I must obey you or you can kill me.\'94
\par \'93But you tried to kill yourself,\'94 the Brain said.
\par The thought unfolded and unfolded in Joao\rquote s awareness.
\par \'93A slave is one who must produce wealth for another,\'94 the Brain said. \'93
There is only one true wealth in all the universe. I have given you some of it. I have given your father and your mate some of it. And your friends. This wealth is living time. Time. Are we slaves because we have given you more time to live?\'94
\par Joao looked up from the voice sac to the giant, glittering eyes. He thought he detected amusement there.
\par \'93We\rquote ve spared and extended the lives of all those who were with you,\'94 the voice drummed. \'93That makes us your slaves, does it not?\'94
\par \'93What do you take in return?\'94 Joao demanded.
\par \'93Ah, hah!\'94 the voice fairly barked. \'93Quid pro quo! That\rquote s this thing called business which I didn\rquote t understand. Your father will leave soon to speak with the men of his government. He is our
 messenger. He trades us his time. He is our slave as well, is it not so? We are tied to each other by the bond of mutual slavery that cannot be broken. It never could be broken\'85 no matter how hard you tried.\'94
\par \'93It\rquote s very simple once you understand the interdependence,\'94 Joao\rquote s father said.
\par \'93Understand what?\'94
\par \'93Some of our kind lived once in greenhouses,\'94 the voice rumbled. \'93Their cells remembered the experience. You know about greenhouses, of course.\'94
\par The giant face turned to look out at the cave mouth, where dawn was beginning to touch the world with gray. \'93That out there, that, too, is a greenhouse.\'94 Again, it peered down at Joao, the giant eyes glittering. \'93
To sustain life, a greenhouse must be maintained in a delicate state of balance by the life within it\emdash 
enough of this chemical, enough of that one, another substance available when required. That which is poison one day can be the sweetest food the next day.\'94
\par \'93What\rquote s all this to do with slavery?\'94 Joao demanded, and he heard the petulance in his own voice.
\par \'93Life has developed through millions of years on greenhouse Earth,\'94 the Brain rumbled. \'93Sometimes it developed in the poison excrement of other life\'85 and then that poison became necessary to it. Without a substance
 produced by wireworms, that savannah grass out there would die\'85 in time.\'94
\par Joao stared up at the rock ceiling, his thoughts turning over like cards in a file. \'93China\rquote s barren earth!\'94 he said.
\par \'93Precisely,\'94 the Brain said. \'93Without substances produced by\'85 }{\i\cf1\insrsid15279183 insects}{\cf1\insrsid15279183 
, and other forms of life, your kind of life would perish. Sometimes just a faint trace of the substance is needed, such as the special copper produced by arachnids. Sometimes the substance must pass through many valences, subtly changed each time, be
fore it can be used by a life form at the end of the chain. Break the chain and all die. The more different forms of life there are, the more life the greenhouse can support. The successful greenhouse must enclose many forms of life\emdash 
the more forms of life, the healthier for all.\'94
\par \'93Chen-Lhu,\'94 Joao said. \'93He could be made to help. He could go with my father, tell them\'85 Did you save Chen-Lhu?\'94
\par \'93The Chinese,\'94 the Brain said. \'93He can be said to live, although you abused him cruelly. The essential structures of the brain are alive, thanks to our prompt action.\'94
\par Joao looked down at the bulging, fissured mass on the floor of the cave. He turned away.
\par \'93They have given me proof to take back with me,\'94 Joao\rquote s father said. \'93There can be no doubt. No one will doubt. We must stop killing and changing insects.\'94
\par \'93And let them take over,\'94 Joao whispered.
\par }{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 \'93We say you must stop killing yourselves,\'94 the voice rumbled. \'93Already the people of your Chen-Lhu are\'85 I believe you would call it }{
\i\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183 reinfesting}{\cf1\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15279183\charrsid15279183  their land. Perhaps they will be in time, perhaps not. 
